# 1️⃣ Binary Search Tree (BST)

---

# First Understand the Problem

Suppose we have numbers:

```text
50 20 70 10 30 60 80
```

We want:

✅ Fast search

✅ Fast insertion

✅ Organized storage

---

# Recall Arrays

```text
10 20 30 40 50
```

Searching can be fast using Binary Search.

But insertion can be expensive.

---

# Recall Linked Lists

Insertion is easy.

But searching is slow.

---

# We want BOTH

```text
Fast Search
+
Fast Insert
```

This leads to BST.

---

# What is a BST?

A BST is a Binary Tree that follows a special rule:

### For every node:

```text
Left subtree  < Node

Right subtree > Node
```

This rule is EVERYTHING.

---

# Example

```text
        50
       /  \
     20    70
    / \    / \
   10 30 60 80
```

Check:

For 50:

```text
Left side:
10 20 30
(all smaller)

Right side:
60 70 80
(all larger)
```

Correct BST ✅

---

# Mental Model

Think of a school principal.

Students with smaller roll numbers:

```text
Go Left
```

Students with larger roll numbers:

```text
Go Right
```

Every node acts like a decision gate.

---

# Why This Rule Matters

Because it allows us to eliminate half the tree while searching.

Exactly like Binary Search.

---

# Searching in BST

Suppose we search:

```text
60
```

Tree:

```text
        50
       /  \
     20    70
    / \    / \
   10 30 60 80
```

---

### Step 1

At:

```text
50
```

Compare:

```text
60 > 50
```

Go right.

Ignore entire left subtree.

---

### Step 2

At:

```text
70
```

Compare:

```text
60 < 70
```

Go left.

---

### Step 3

At:

```text
60
```

Found.

---

# Mental Model

```text
BST Search
=
Playing "Guess My Number"
```

You continuously eliminate wrong regions.

---

# Why It Is Fast

Every comparison removes roughly half of the remaining possibilities.

Just like Binary Search.

---

# BST Insertion

Suppose tree is:

```text
      50
     /  \
   20    70
```

Insert:

```text
60
```

---

### Step 1

Compare:

```text
60 > 50
```

Go right.

---

### Step 2

Compare:

```text
60 < 70
```

Go left.

---

### Step 3

Empty spot.

Insert.

---

Result:

```text
      50
     /  \
   20    70
         /
       60
```

---

# Key Insight

Insertion follows the same path as searching.

---

# Important Placement Fact 🔥

### Inorder Traversal of BST

Always produces:

```text
Sorted Order
```

Example:

```text
        50
       /  \
     20    70
    / \    / \
   10 30 60 80
```

Inorder:

```text
10 20 30 50 60 70 80
```

Sorted.

Interviewers ask this very often.

---

# How to Remember Forever

```text
BST Rule

Left < Root < Right
```

Everything comes from this rule.

---

# 2️⃣ Why BST Searching is Faster than Linked Lists

---

# Let's Compare

Suppose we need to find:

```text
80
```

---

## Linked List

```text
10 → 20 → 30 → 40 → 50 → 60 → 70 → 80
```

---

Must check:

```text
10
20
30
40
50
60
70
80
```

One by one.

---

# Time Complexity

```text
O(n)
```

---

# Why?

Because linked lists have no ordering logic.

You cannot skip nodes.

---

# BST

```text
        50
       /  \
     20    70
    / \    / \
   10 30 60 80
```

---

Search 80:

### Compare with 50

Go right.

---

### Compare with 70

Go right.

---

### Found 80

Only 3 comparisons.

---

# Time Complexity

Average:

```text
O(log n)
```

Much faster.

---

# Real-World Analogy

### Linked List

Finding a name in an unsorted notebook.

You read line by line.

---

### BST

Finding a word in a dictionary.

You keep narrowing the search.

Much faster.

---

# Why BST Is Powerful

Combines:

### Binary Search Logic

```text
Fast Search
```

with

### Tree Structure

```text
Easy Insert/Delete
```

---

# When BST Becomes Bad

Interviewers often ask this.

Suppose insertion order:

```text
10
20
30
40
50
```

Tree becomes:

```text
10
  \
   20
     \
      30
        \
         40
           \
            50
```

Looks like a linked list.

---

# Problem

Searching becomes:

```text
O(n)
```

again.

---

# Mental Model

```text
Balanced BST
=
Good

Skewed BST
=
Bad
```

This is why advanced trees like AVL Trees and Red-Black Trees exist.

(We'll learn later.)

---

# Comparison Table

| Feature                | Linked List            | BST               |
| ---------------------- | ---------------------- | ----------------- |
| Search                 | O(n)                   | O(log n) average  |
| Insert                 | O(1) at known position | O(log n) average  |
| Ordering               | No                     | Yes               |
| Binary Search Possible | No                     | Yes-like behavior |

---

